Obese baby menu: does not eat and eat sausages
More than a third of children 9 to 13 years of age have weight problems, with overweight being 9 percent of schoolchildren and obese 5 percent of children.
Obese children mostly come from families with unhealthy lifestyles, as the current survey showed.
Again, it shows how important it is to the healthy development of a person’s environment in which he grows and the patterns by which he is surrounded.
For example, sausages appear up to half more often on tables in obese children than in families with normal weight.
Fried fries had for dinner the day before the research related to an educational event called Obesity is not a coincidence of more than 19 percent obese.
In fat families, it is also not customary to play sports, but this applies to most families of today's schoolchildren - only 15 percent of the children replied that their parents will find time to move actively at least once a week.
A Survey Among 900 Children
The survey took place at the end of last year's school year and was attended by almost 900 children from primary schools from all over the Czech Republic.
It was already the second year of the Obesity event is not a coincidence supported by the General Health Insurance Company and Unilever.
So far, more than 12,000 schoolchildren from the 4th to 8th grade have been involved in the project.
The proper eating and sufficient movement in the family is one of the determining factors that causes a dramatically increasing number of overweight or even obesity children.
"Only half of the polled said, for example, that they eat five times a day in breakfast-dinner-dinner-dinner mode, which is one of the basic prerequisites of proper nutrition," one of the results of the survey.
No breakfast and no sausage at night
Experts point out that there are important and relative details for healthy development, such as regular family breakfast times.
In the Czech Republic, only 23 percent of schoolchildren's families eat breakfast at the same time.
In most families, everyone eats breakfast alone.
And the worst thing was finding out that in a tenth of the households, there's no breakfast at all.
Breakfast is the basis of the right daily diet.
A questionnaire showed that unhealthy fries are consumed more often in families of obese children.
Almost everyone - regardless of weight - drinks sweet sodas every day (70 percent).
Although more than 40 percent of the children polled regularly, the result was less than half - 15 percent for their parents.
Build your diet
Another part of the survey allowed selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to compile their own diets from the offered options according to their own tastes and their own opinions.
"The dietary preferences of Czech children aged 12 to 15 are far from ideal in terms of healthy nutrition."
Among their favorite foods are a lot of flour, meat and sweet dishes.
"The alarming is particularly popular with sweet lemonade," the final survey report states.
For lunch as a main dish, pasta just over the poultry won.
But the children practically didn't want legumes at all and the popularity of fish and lunch vegetables is low.
Adaptation to Health
At the same time, the survey showed that children are willing to adjust their eating habits if they get the right information.
"There has been a significant shift in preferences towards the principles of healthy nutrition in a number of cases in the control group of survey participants who completed the questionnaire after the end of the Obesity education lecture," the project results.
For example, it was notable for sweet lemonade, where more children would begin to prefer ordinary water.
Children also checked the poultry and fish questionnaire more frequently as the main meal of the day and would limit sweet meals and dumplings.
