In Need for Speed: The Run is raced across America.
Review
Originally a carefree ride is transformed into a routine morning shift journey due to a series of completely unnecessary sloppy mistakes.
Ambition was largely fulfilled, but it is of little use when no one apparently wanted to do anything extra.
The new episode with the subtitle The Run raised high expectations before the release.
He promised that the old race series Need for Speed would once again move a bit in a new direction and from playable demonstrations he appeared as a game that might not be in the genre of action racing just to number.
We were also curious to see how the inserted passages would end, in which the main hero would step out of the car and take place on foot.
However, as is the case with the NFS series, many are a little different than we expected.
These are potentially decent arcade races, but the whole pulls down a few unnecessary mistakes that have appeared in the series more or less for several years.
So it's not really mistakes, but it's a manifestation of the incomprehensible laziness of developers.
The adventure begins very well.
You are inducted into a story whose main hero Jack has certain personal issues and as a solution is offered to participate in an illegal race across America.
You sit behind the wheel on the west coast of San Francisco, and your task is to arrive first in New York.
The idea carries several interesting elements.
The route is divided into ten stages, and then more than fifty races.
It follows that each race is on a different track and the stages are set in different, sufficiently different and interesting environments.
One doesn't feel like the game's offering the same thing for a second.
Some of the environments are also very pretty to look at, although the technical level of graphics corresponds to the previous parts of the series.
So it's not a big deal.
But driving across the desert, the autumn landscape or high in the snowy mountains seems visually very pleasant.
Moreover, from time to time, races are amplified by an uncharacteristic element.
In the desert, for example, you get involved in a sandstorm that greatly reduces visibility.
In the mountains, on the other hand, you must be careful not to be buried by avalanches.
In addition, individual races are quite well placed in a row.
There's only a few types, but that's enough.
For a while you try to overtake the desired number of opponents (essentially classic race), then you catch up with time (classical fight with stopwatches) and then there is a duel waiting for you with only one opponent.
From time to time, the police will also get involved in this, which makes your efforts even more difficult.
New are passages outside the car.
It's more of an interactive animation where Jack usually flees from someone and you have to help him by printing the right buttons at the right moment.
Nothing complicated.
They will surprise, however, that these passages are in play much less than you would expect (specifically perhaps even three).
In the end, however, it is for the benefit of the thing, because this element has no chance of becoming annoying and in the context of the above mentioned, it ranks among the elements that arouse the game.
The ride model follows in the footsteps of previous episodes.
This means that these days it is certainly no longer anything, but it cannot be said that it is a negative.
If you're looking for a realistic simulation, you'll have to look elsewhere.
But the more active racing of the local riding model still suits quite well, even though we would be able to find a better one in the competition.
Until then, everything's perfectly all right.
Problems begin to appear after a while.
Unlike the driving model, the collision model is no longer correct.
We do not expect this type of game to count complex deformations and collisions, but if you have virtually no idea how your car will behave, then everything is probably not all right.
Typically, when you drive or pass cars in normal traffic, you sometimes lick each other lightly, but other times in an almost identical situation, your car ends up in wild pirouettes.
Or even attack.
The reboot system doesn't seem to be a big deal, but it'll make you feel better.
The reboots are designed so that if you break down or go far off the track, the game throws you back to the last clue point on the track.
Only five reboots are available in each race.
When you exhaust them, you have to start the race all over again.
So it's more of a tool in case something goes wrong than if you could rely on them explicitly.
Sometimes reboots will not help, however, they will be solved by the need to learn a given section of the race by heart.
The big setback of the game is that the same things often happen in the same places.
For example, some turns need to be driven in a specific way, otherwise you simply can't fit into them.
Other times, you will meet "civil" cars in the same configuration at the same location, whether you arrive first, fifth, five seconds earlier or one minute later.
It pisses off especially in situations where you can see how the opponent will easily pass between two opposing cars in front of you, while when you get there, the cars are already in such a position that you have to drive around or brake them.
It doesn't matter when you get to them, because it's "counted" so that the situation always happens right in front of your nose.
Competitors have another advantage.
In all the time playing, you come across several places where you, again regardless of the time, always overtake the same opponent in the same place.
The most hits at the end of the game on a long bridge where you drive in the opposite direction.
The enemy must get there in front of you at any cost, apparently.
When you drive in front of you, you get a worse view of the opposing cars, so at first, you're probably going to have a couple of bumps.
You can understand the intention to make the game more exciting and adrenalineier, but the design is so obvious that it makes you reliably quickly disgusted.
And it's a shame, because despite the simple driving model, playing is fun and sometimes action enough that sometimes you literally can't watch where it flies.
And it doesn't really matter whether the concept of 50 unique tracks, the order of races, is responsible for it, so that boring doesn't stand a chance, or anything else.
An unusual idea is the exchange of cars during races.
You have to watch out for gas stations near the roads, because that's where you can change the car, although in most cases, you'll get by with what you just have.
Cars are divided into three categories.
The sports cars are suitable for urban areas, strong U.S. vehicles on straight highways and exotic supercars for technical riding, for example on winding mountain roads.
With the main story mode it goes hand in hand and mode of challenges, which are races in individual locations you know from the story.
Here you get not only medals, but also experience points to your profile, which is common for both challenges and story.
Various items are unlocked for gaining a higher level of driver: starting with cars and ending with backgrounds for profile.
It is also linked to the online Autolog function, which compares your achievements with other players and provides other community functions.
One of the other hard to understand kicks is the situation from the last race in the story.
With your car you can reach the subway tunnel (but so), where you drive it in the dark on the tracks (but so).
On the speedometer, the numbers between 150 and 200 km/h (if so) flash, and there comes a train set from behind and uncompromisingly scrapes you.
In the editor's office, we will probably still have a few more days to talk about whether no one really gave a little thought when creating the game, or whether the authors think we're really that big an idiot.
The technical side of the game is nothing special, but at least the overall visual impression is very pleasant in most cases and even great in a few cases.
It is so saddened that, in some tenser moments, the images are dropping, and in some cases quite tragically.
However, this concerns mainly accidents with a larger number of participants, when continuous scanning would not be of any use to you anyway.
The sound page is fine and the soundtrack is a matter of taste.
In an effort to please the widest possible range of younger audiences, a soundtrack from the category of "every dog different village" was created, but one can assume that because of listening to music, someone will probably not just buy the game.
The overall impression of Need for Speed: The Run is so greatly embarrassed.
If the game were to avoid completely unnecessary mistakes, then we would not be afraid to say that The Run has been the best NFS work in years.
But this is how the game works undone.
I'm sure it's fun, but get ready for mistakes to blow your eyes with the power of airport spotlights.
