History of IBM: From Cheese Slicer to Flight to Space
IBM (International Business Machines) was formed in New York a hundred years ago, originally having a complex name Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
The name IBM was taken over only in 1924 - originally it was a brand used for branches of the company in Canada and South America.
The merger of four companies, whose history dates back to the 1880s, gave the basis to the later IBM.
They owned technologies such as famous "pointers," which means clocks recording employees' arrival and departure.
The architect of the new firm was businessman Charles Ranlett Flint, who also presided over the company's supervisory board until 1930.
Flint hired rival company chief Thomas J. Watson to help him manage the company.
The leader then overshadowed the founder of IBM - an unbeatable corporate culture and identity is still built on Watson's ideas.
Watson ran the company until 1952.
IBM, as its name suggests, started producing and selling all kinds of machines for business - from meat and cheese cutters to cash registers.
During the first four years that Watson was in charge of the firm, the turnover doubled to $9 million and the company's extensive expansion began to all continents.
Watson was so indispensable to the company that after nearly forty years in the chief chair he was replaced by his son, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his leadership, IBM began working on the development of artificial intelligence, developing the first programming language.
In the 1960s, people and computers from IBM helped NASA fly into space - to Mercury, Saturn and in 1969 the famous human flight to the Moon.
Meanwhile, in 1964, IBM developed the first family of computers - the IBM System/360 series.
The classic "basket," which established the computer standard of the time, called IBM 5150, came on the market in 1981.
Twenty years later, IBM sold computers to Chinese company Lenovo, on the contrary, bought a consulting part of PricewaterhouseCoopers and began to fully engage in advice and services with high added value.
