How prices of tours have developed since 1989
Until 1989, only five state travel agencies were allowed in Czechoslovakia: Chedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autotourist.
Travel agents at the time sold only tours to socialist bloc countries in the vast majority, as travel to the west was very limited.
Czech tourists thus travelled on vacation to the sea in the GDR (German Democratic Republic), the Soviet Union (Sochi in Crimea near the Black Sea), Bulgaria, Romania (both to the Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
The light exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when it was possible to travel to Yugoslavia as well, but then the Yugoslav regime inclined to the West and the trips of Czech tourists to Yugoslavia were subsequently very limited.
The great paradox of the time of socialism was that the citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e. also the Czechoslovaks) were not allowed to travel individually even within socialist countries.
If the citizen of Czechoslovakia wanted to travel individually to Poland or the Soviet Union for example, he needed an invitation letter from this country, otherwise the individual way was not possible.
Travel agencies also offered tours to the West at the time, but it was necessary to stand the line overnight with a sleeping bag or to have "good friends" in the travel agency.
Still, it was not won.
The so-called foreign exchange promise, which was a condition for travel to the West, was not granted to "politically unreliable people" who could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely convertible currency, so without a foreign exchange promise it was not possible to raise funds (western currency) for the trip to the West.
By far, however, the Czechs mostly spent their holidays in the Czech Republic, resulting in a large number of cottages and cottages that the Czechs acquired and this custom survives to this day.
Czech travel has thus experienced a real revolution since 1989.
While the holiday in the GDR or Bulgaria was our maximum until 1989, last year Czechs spent 4.5 million vacations abroad in countries around the world.
The huge paradox that we are no longer aware of today is that it was not possible for us to travel freely to the most popular Croatia until 1989 because it was part of Yugoslavia.
Immediately from the early 1990s, visa requirements were lifted to neighbouring western European countries, triggering a huge wave of short-term visits mainly from Austria’s Vienna or Germany.
The Czechoslovaks could not get enough of trips to the West for a long time, everyone wanted to look there for a while.
In Paris, for example, Czech tours slept in parks in tents, as our incomes at that time did not allow us to pay for a hotel or guesthouse.
A typical feature of Czech travel at this time was the carriage of their own food, cans, salamis, etc., to save money.
Another important moment was the introduction of a freely convertible Czech crown, which allowed our tourists to finally purchase the Western currency after many tens of years.
However, our standard of living and, with it, average salaries were rising, resulting in another important moment around 1997.
Thanks to the increased demand for travel, travel agencies began to regularly prepare tours with charter flights since 1997, making air tours incredibly cheaper due to the possibility of arranging quantity discounts compared to the past.
By the end of the 1990s, Czechs had already had visa-free contact with virtually all developed countries of the world, except the US, which continued to facilitate our travel.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolutionary travel occurred right in 2000, when due to considerable demand he was sent from the Czech Republic historically the first direct charter flight to exotics, it was to Thailand.
Since this year, direct charters fly with Czech tourists to warm faraway countries, this winter will fly directly from the Czech Republic to twelve exotic destinations.
Exotic countries currently visit around 100,000 Czechs annually!
Another interesting moment in this period, which symbolizes our post-revolutionary development, came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the US cancelled visas for Czech tourists, thus definitely ranked our country among the world's most advanced countries.
In 2008, the Czechs also spent more than half of their holidays abroad for the first time in history (50.3%) and spent more than 15 thousand CZK per person for the first time in history for one foreign holiday, including the cost of a place of residence.
