An emotionally strong new book by Peter Englund called Beauty and Grief: The Confidential History of World War I (The Beauty and the Sorrow: An Intimate History of the First World War) begins with such a long list of performing characters until your head spins.
One piece of advice on how to act at that moment: Carefully tear this page out and make a bookmark out of it.
You will get to know everyone in the novel narrative of Mr. Englund very well and this list will serve you as a navigation - like a lighthouse - at times when, like men and women in the story, you will feel confused and lost in different situations.
Mr Englund is a Swedish historian and journalist.
He is also the new deputy at the Swedish Academy, which awards the Nobel Prize for Literature.
The book we are talking about here is very unusual - the author describes it himself, quite aptly, as an "antihistorical work".
It contains several very well-known names, important contracts or famous battles, on the contrary, almost lacking ambassadors, energetic journalists, and debates on tactics and equipment.
It's not so much a book about what happened as the author explains, rather than "a book about what it was like". It mainly deals with "feelings, impressions, experiences and moods".
"Beauty and grief" combines war experiences of 20 more or less dozen men and women, on both sides of the barricade, from students and botanists to mountaineers, doctors, ambulance drivers and officials.
Some of these people become heroes.
Others become prisoners of war, lose limbs, go crazy or die.
Their lives are blended like the flames of candles lit in a church - new ones are added to the entanglement of fate, while others are extinguishing.
Mr. Englund's book differs from classic historical novels.
It corrects the idea that World War I was just about the terrifying trenches on the West Front.
"Beauty and grief" skillfully explores other places where war dramas took place: Alps, Balkans, Eastern Front, Mesopotamia, East Africa.
Soldiers in this book solve problems with bee nests falling on them, must spend Christmas in the shadow of the pyramids or struggle with the presence of tsetse flies.
Almost from the beginning, it is a very moving reading.
War consumes people's lives like some kind of natural disaster, like Hurricane Katrina smelling of gunpowder.
When gunfire starts to sound in the distance, and you're the woman who's home with your children, run away or stay?
Who's coming?
Almost no one understands what is happening, not even why the entire war was unleashed.
"Vakuum arising from lack of facts," observed Mr. Englund, "was filled with conjectures, conjectures, hopes, fears, prejudices, conspiracy theories, dreams, nightmares, and rumours."
"Beauty and Grief" follows the stories of individuals such as Florence Farmborough, an English nurse in the Russian Army, and Richard Stumpf, a young sailor serving in the German fleet.
Their stories are mostly taken from résumés, letters and other already published materials.
The descriptions of their lives may sound both frightening and engaging, but thanks to the integration of tiny moments and details they are absolutely vivid and believable.
Many of them deal with suffering and coping with it.
In the story of a German student, the author says, "Counters, everywhere, all substitutes."
"Coffete substitute, aluminum imitation, rubber imitation, paper bandages, wooden buttons."
It goes even further and describes food substitutes in Germany.
It mentions "mass made from pressed rice cooked in mutton fat (and supplemented with a false bone of wood), tobacco from dried roots and dried potato peels, boots with wooden soles".
It mentions that there were "837 registered meat substitutes in the production of sausages and 511 registered coffee substitutes".
Some stories are about honor and bravery.
One American finds internal impulses for savagery and brutality, then declares of war: "In the end you will understand that this is human nature. Not to sit in comfortable chairs with cigarettes and whiskey, evening newspapers or good books, and pretend that this mask of yours represents civilization and that there is no barbarian hiding behind the starched self inside."
On the contrary, the British soldier realizes that he will most likely die soon and no one will even notice, let alone grieve.
