Although Breivik could have acted alone, he was certainly not lonely in cyberspace: he spent a lot of time at the computer during the preparation of the attack, chatting with some of the millions of nationalists supporting right-wing groups on social networking sites.
After the tragedy of this summer, scientists want to learn more about these people.
But how do you find them?
Easy - just go on Facebook.
"We realized that finding them is not really that hard," says Jamie Bartlett, the lead author of the recently released news from the British research team, which concerned European digital populism.
The stock of personal information on Facebook is so extensive, Bartlett says that it was enough for scientists to simply use the advertising on the site and, thanks to this, they determined with complete accuracy the demographic group - something that marketing workers have been doing for years.
Bartlett’s team across Europe found half a million right-wing group fans, then focused attention on them and sent them ads. However, instead of inviting them to the newly formed group or offering them some dietary products, they invited them to fill out a questionnaire asking questions about their level of education, their relation to violence and optimism in view of their own future.
Through Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues managed to get results from over 10,000 fans of 14 different right-wing groups in 11 European countries - without ever having to leave the office.
"It's a whole new way of doing research," Bartlett notes.
Some of the results are not so surprising: online supporters of right-wing groups are mostly young men who are disgusted by the increasing rate of immigration.
But on the other hand, "those who combine their online activism with offline activism are more sensible, democratic and less violent than those who remain constantly hidden behind the computer screen."
DEMOS team work is just one example of how Facebook becomes a new tool in the hands of scientists.
Research teams, health scientists, and political researchers use this site to study everything, from health problems to social trends that hide state updates, wall contributions and pressed "I like" buttons.
Facebook reports more than 800 million active users. Each of them provides three different data on average each day, making this social network literally "information supernova", which is behind the development of many new researches. The number of academic works in whose name the word Facebook occurs has risen to almost 800% compared to the state five years ago.
For some scientists, the Facebook spell lies in giving them the opportunity to study people without having to harass them somewhere on the street.
"Formerly, when you wanted to do a survey among people from the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them."
"You'd have to get to the side where they'd never let you go" Bartlett says.
"All this Facebook is breaking down - you're just going straight to them."
Others claim that the site can offer a way to identify and avoid a social-health problem.
In a recent study by Dr Megan Moren of the University of Wisconsin, the research team found that university students who discussed their drunken outputs on Facebook were much more at risk of the problem of alcoholism than students who kept quiet about the subject.
Moren suggests that peers of students monitor the site and come up with an offer to help a student who publishes too many drunken statuses.
"The problem cannot be solved if you can't diagnose it," said Washington Post Dimitri Christakis, co-author of Dr. Moren and director of the Center for Health, Behavior and Development of Children at the Seattle Children's Research Institute.
"We have found a way to identify endangered children we would otherwise not have a chance to discover."
Facebook itself constantly probes the data of its users.
The site's information team has developed statistics on relations status and Valentine's Day, voting participation in 2010 and the nation's satisfaction coefficient (mainly using the information they had access to - Internet freedom advocates have long claimed that the site should make its information treasure available to research and others).
But Facebook users know that the site is watching them, whether they like it or not - in exchange for the opportunity to play Scrabble with a friend who is thousands of miles away, you need to provide your personal information to the site.
But what if Facebook users become part of a research they don't even know about?
Scientists have clearly defined rules regarding how to collect data offline. However, online data is accessible to everyone.
"I don't think most users thought scientists could look into their profiles," says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at London Knowledge Lab, about a 2006 study he conducted using the public Facebook walls of his students.
"As far as they were concerned, they took it as being information between them and their friends."
Subsequently, the question of methodology is also considered.
Even with off-line research, there is no guarantee that the subject is absolutely sincere.
There is no way to verify on Facebook how much information on the profile and posts on the wall are true.
"What you say on Facebook and what you do off Facebook are two completely different things," Selwyn explains.
That is why Selwin, who has spent years researching new technologies, thinks that pencil and notebook remain the best possible tool that can be used in research.
