There are cases where teachers themselves give their students test answers just to make themselves look good in their assessments.
Mentors who should teach the opposite send a message that lies and deceit are acceptable.
How many frauds do we encounter?
Studies show that in one day, you lie somewhere between 10 and 200 cases.
Suppose many of them are merciful lies.
Another study showed that strangers had lied three times in the first ten minutes of their first encounter in life.
Determining lies, or "recognising lies", is a necessary skill that anyone should acquire, whether for personal or work reasons.
However, it is not a social game that is similar, say, to Sharada, when one shouts, "I have you." Recognizing deception is a serious sector of science working with scientific data collected over the last six decades at prestigious universities during detailed research projects, especially in the field of psychology and philosophy.
One of the results of the research is that most of the old myths about lies have been refuted.
Liars look you in the eye.
It's not like they're squirming, stuttering, blushing or squirming.
But do not conclude that it is somehow difficult to spot and expose liars.
A trained lie identifier can reveal the truth from a sentence structure, small facial expressions, the way questions are created and their timing.
I have spent several years gathering scientific knowledge from an extensive and emerging sector regarding the recognition of lies, and it is clear that the detection of deception is a modern skill that can be easily learned and can be of great help in today's complicated world - especially if your work responsibilities include hiring, holding interviews, negotiating or leading people.
Good liars can read well in others, letting them be alert, directing their emotions, and intuitively realizing how the other side accepts them.
From research we know that extroverts lie more often than introverts, that men tell more "self-centered" lies, while women say more lies "focused on others" - mostly to protect someone's feelings - that married people lie less often to their partners than free people (but the lies they say are usually "unspeakable").
We also know that if you are perceived as a sinner, others feel less guilty when they lie to you.
How do you know someone's lying?
First, observe the subject's normal behavior.
It's called initial observation.
Thanks to him, he'll have something to compare later on.
Notice the subject's posture, his laughter, his voice work.
You should know if someone routinely constantly taps their legs so you don't wrongfully accuse him of lying just because he starts to tap his feet in the middle of a meeting.
Then try to identify clusters of false verbal and non-verbal behavior.
But consider it only as warning signals, not as proof of a lie.
People who tell lies can stop moving the upper half of the body while trying to remember their fictional story, the shoe tips can turn to the door, lean towards the exit, significantly change the posture, or show "relief after the end of the interview" - excessive relief of breath and position change when the confession is difficult behind them.
Often interviewers give a false signal that the interview is over, just to see what relief will look like after it ends.
Feel also the language of the subject.
Famous is the story of how Scott Peterson once misrepresented himself and used past tense to claim that his murdered wife was alive, triggering a nationwide search for her body.
Deceiving individuals may also express themselves measuredly: "I had no sexual relationship with that lady... Miss Lewinsky" or they repeat the difficult question.
The most common verbal characteristics are very slight.
Someone can use a lot of "melting language" when he answers the difficult question, "Well... to be honest... from what I know... to my best knowledge."
We don't know a lot of facts in such an answer, and it's often another warning signal.
There is no spell to reveal every lie, but it is possible to master the skills that can be used to stalk a lie.
With these skills, one will have a better chance of not falling for a liar and a fraud in his personal and work life.
