Climate Disaster Slowed the Economy
During the first year of the reign of Maria López Valdez, unemployment and unreliability increased in Sinaloa, foreign investment declined and with them the economy
This is the first year of the reign of Maria López Valdez, which is called the government of change itself, and this government has brought with it great expectations in terms of economic progress, but no growth was recorded due to adverse climatic conditions at the beginning of the year and even the main indicators of economic development have declined.
Low February temperatures caused millions of losses in agriculture, limited the possibilities of growth of the state economy, resulting in a reduction in economic activity of 3.6% in the first semester of this year. In agriculture, there was a historical decline of 31.16%, which disrupted the dynamics of other economic sectors as well.
According to the report on the damage caused by the Mexican Council for Sustainable Rural Development, the damage was recorded at 582 835 hectares of cultivated land, 78.03% of which was completely destroyed and partial damage was found at the remaining 21.07%. The main destroyed crops include vegetables, maize and games.
According to the National Institute for Statistics and Geography, the unemployment rate in the state experienced an increased increase during the first three quarters. From January to March, 55,053 residents of Sinaloa state were unemployed, representing an unemployment rate of 4.53% of the economically active population. In the second quarter, unemployment increased to 5.28% and between July and August, average unemployment continued to rise and reached 6.19%, representing approximately 74,000 unemployed people.
Less liquidity
More factors are responsible for unemployment during the year in the state of Sinaloa. According to Gerard López Cervantes, Director of the Faculty of Economic and Social Sciences of the UAS, the increase in unemployment can be explained indirectly, based on actions taken at the level of public policy.
"We are witnessing increasing unemployment, which is linked to various factors, including the loss of liquidity in the market due to the reduction of resources due to legislation passed by Congress in connection with the fight against money laundering. It is not easy for people who illegally seize dollars to make money, invest them or use them for anything," he stressed.
Stopping Migration
López Cervantes said that a demographic factor is also involved in the increase in unemployment.
"The number of people who go abroad to work in the United States has declined, both because of difficult entry and then because even if these people get abroad, it is hard for them to get a job. People remain and demand work from our state, and thus unemployment is rising", he said.
Unreliability
According to the National Institute for Statistics and Democracy, 60.38% of the state’s employed people work without taking social security benefits.
Other labour market features such as low salaries are added to unemployment and unreliability. In this administrative territory there are the lowest salaries from all over the country, as reported by the Mexican Institute of Social Security and the Labour Secretariat and Social Planning.
The average monthly income of workers in the state of Sinaloa was by September 5,352 pesetas, deep below the national average, which ranges on the amount of 7,375 pesetas.
Reduction of foreign direct investment
Along with the decline in economic activity and the increase in unemployment, the most significant decline in foreign direct investment in the last 10 years has also been recorded in 2011. According to the Ministry of Finance, foreign direct investment amounted to $630,697 between January and June, representing a decrease of 87.74% compared to $5,14,312 for the same period in the previous year.
On the other hand, the Ministry for Economic Development of the Government of the State lists investments of 17 280 million pesetas per year.
Debt
In the context of the economic downturn scenario, the government of this state asked the state Congress in July to approve a loan of 3 billion pesos, which would be intended to invest in infrastructure projects in 18 urban areas in order to revive the economy. The local Congress approved a loan of 2 600 million pesos. By November, no debt gains were recorded in any sector of the state economy.
Reactions
According to the representatives of the business sector, the first year of the reign of Mario López Valdés pointed out a lack of governing powers of the government.
Miguel Loredo López, chairman of the National Chamber of Transformation Industry, stated that in 2011 the will of individual sectors, including the government itself, was lacking.
"The development of the economy in Sinaloa was really small during this year. We have to work intensively to get back the land we lost this year. In 2012 we have to double our efforts, the harmonisation of the efforts of all of us and, in particular, the correct and synchronized functioning of this new government. Hopefully, next year will be much better", he said.
Slowness of the economy
Loredo López stated that events like frosts in the beginning of the year stopped the state economy and limited its development and growth.
"Weak economic movement was caused by a number of events, including frosts. One of the main consequences was the slowdown of the economy, which did not recover quickly enough to restore dynamism, which would enable us to achieve an acceptable level of movement of processes, products and services. That is why we found ourselves well below the expected forecasts at the end of the year", he said.
Re-defining the mission
According to Teodor Salazar Uriart, President of the Employment Confederation of the Republic of Mexico in Sinaloa, it is necessary to push the state towards more dynamic productive activities.
"Generally speaking, we observe that work is being done. We believe that a long-term plan should be prepared, in which the objectives and economic direction of the state would be redefined, because it is important that all the potential material and human resources that Sinaloa has be mobilised", he said.
Work That Is Before Us
Chairman Coparmex stressed the importance of establishing a vision of the future that would better manage the government's efforts.
"In general, I would say that the government has tried to achieve good results in various areas, there have been some progress in the area of economic development, but it is important to create a long-term plan", he said.
He stated that the current administration showed progress with regard to public policy leadership.
"There are elements that make it possible to claim that the government is trying to be friendly. I can say that there is work done here and I believe that the government is aware that there is also a lot of work ahead of us", he said.
