In Michoacán they analyze the possibility of counting "voice by voice"
According to the figures published by PREP, the difference between the first and second place in the governor's election is less than 27 percent. So far, the votes of 879 of the 6074 electoral districts have not been counted.
The possibility of counting "voice after vote" appeared in this year's Michoacán election, where, in accordance with the data published by the Preliminary Election Results Programme (PREP), the difference between the first and second place in the governor's election was less than 27 percent, and 879 votes from a total of 6074 electoral districts have not yet been counted.
In this context, the Chair of the General Electoral Institute of Michoacán (IEM), María de los Ángeles Llanderal Zaragoza, recalled that a few days ago, on November 9, the electoral authority approved a number of measures that should harmonise local standards with federal electoral reform.
As will be noted, Michoacán did not officially confirm his political constitution or his State Electoral Code or the Law on Election Justice. The State Congress approved the reforms shortly before the legal deadline for their entry into force was due to expire during this term, and Governor Leonel Godoy Rangel neglected their publication within the prescribed deadline in the Act of the Official State Gazette, stating that he had any objections against them.
On November 9, the Supreme State Court (SCJN) resolved the constitutional dispute initiated by the local legislative power and declared the head of state's vote on constitutional reforms "unvalid and illegal" because it has no right to "neither approve nor veto them".
On the question of the possibility of a 'voice-to-voice' census, María de los Ángeles Llanderal replied that by approving the relevant measures, the General Council of the IEM would allow the local electoral body to carry out both partial and total censuses.
In this way, a partial census of votes, one or more electoral packages, will be possible under the following conditions: election results do not agree; there is no record of the census and calculation in the appropriate box or the chair does not have it available; or if errors and obvious violations of electoral results have occurred.
In addition, the total recount of votes in all ballot boxes will be possible if there is evidence suggesting that the difference between the potential winner of the election and the candidate in second place is less or equal to one percentage point; whenever an explicit request by the party representative and/or coalition that proposed the candidate in second place appears at the beginning of the session.
The total count of votes will also be possible when, after a proper census, it is found that the difference between the likely winner and the candidate in the second place is equal to or less than one percentage point, and also if there is an explicit request from the political party whose candidate finished in the second place. In this case, the electoral packages for which a partial census has been made will be eliminated.
It should be noted that in such a situation there is an election in Morelia, where according to PREP the difference between the first and second place is less than 0.16%, although 129 of the total 923 electoral districts have not yet been added up.
