The appointed Prime Minister Mario Monti will meet with the Italian President tomorrow to present him with a new government that will face the crisis that is holding this country under the brink of economic disaster, which has put the entire euro area in danger.
The Presidential Palace issued a report announcing that Monti, named on Sunday, will meet with President Giorgio Napolitano on Wednesday to confirm to him that he can form a government.
It is expected to present a government composed mostly of technocrats, although it is not yet clear when the new government will take power.
Monti stated that he would present to the President the results of his talks with political parties in an effort to form a government.
"I want to confirm that I have absolute confidence in our country's ability to overcome this difficult stage", said the former European Commissioner to journalists.
Monti explicitly did not say that he would be able to form a government, but the tone of his comments suggested that obstacles were overcome.
"The frame is now well marked", he added.
Monti completed the process of forming a government in less than three days, much shorter than usual. Meanwhile, Italy is trying to combat the political and financial crisis, which has made the debt rise to unsustainable levels.
The new administration, led by former European Commissioner Monti, must approve a tough package of austerity that is required by European leaders, and that will be the only way to restore Italy's damaged credibility.
Due to the instability of the markets, the interest on Italian BTP bonds with a 10-year maturity of 7 percentage points exceeded the level at which Greece and Ireland had to ask for rescue.
