First of all, I don't think any of us could imagine being in one big rock group and staying in it for more than 20 years, sounds like a dream.
We realize how much we have been given and we are touched that we can continue to play together.
We love each other and we like to make music.
We're lucky to see the places we've always wanted.
We couldn't have done better.
What did it mean to you that you were an important part of the emergence of the grunge genre?
It has always been an honor for us to be part of this group in which all the greats are represented.
The people of Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains are our friends.
Surprisingly, when a movement emerges from a group of friends, it does not often happen.
From time to time, a group is formed in the city, but it is much less common for five to ten groups to emerge from one city at a time.
We're proud of it, and we're honored to be part of a group from Seattle.
Sometimes we still play with some.
Last year we were at the Alice in Chains festival and we were in Canada with Mudhoney, we saw Soundgarden on tour. We are lucky that they are all our friends and we are honored that we can be part of this movement that originated in Seattle.
It's also very unusual for a group like yours to stick together and still have the same members after all these years.
Yes, the four of us have been together for 21 years and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago, which in itself is much longer than the usual duration of the group.
I think, first of all, we're all lucky that we're still in this world, and second of all, the fact that we're constantly interested in each other plays a role.
We are all close friends, and thanks to this we have managed to open up musical paths that allow everyone sufficient freedom to experiment.
We trust each other, we appreciate each other's music, and I don't think it could be better.
Your relationship to the word fame was not easy, but thanks to your success, you can do what you like.
How do you find balance?
As we grew, it became increasingly easier to find balance.
We try not to travel too much on tour because it is very easy to fall into this trap of crowds and people who love our music.
When you realize that people came because of music, you remember that you have to respect music and what you gave her, you can't get carried away by being famous, rock stars, neither of us really cared about that.
How do you remember the next Mother Love Bone project?
I think we wrote great songs, and it was something spectacular at the beginning.
As a band, we existed for three years and never released an album until after Andy (Andrew Woods) died.
It was very frustrating because it took so long. The most important thing is that today we are friends with Bruce (Fairweather) and Greg (Gilmore) who started in the band with us. When I listen to a song or look at pictures, I remember Andy, how incredible he was, how I laughed with him. It was always a pleasure to work with him, laugh, talk about music or football and so many others.
She was an incredible person, and we miss her so much.
The national band Las Robertas will be commissioned to start the show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you know their work, especially Eddie Vedder, and that that's why you chose them as openers?
Yes, production has sent us videos with several suggestions and we liked this group the most. Therefore, we are curious what Las Robertas offers live and must be very entertaining.
Why do you always change the words of Yellow Ledbetter live?
That's an Ed question, so I don't know.
He sings it, and I think he adds the first thing to his mind.
Who influences you as a bass player?
Lots of people.
I'm the first to think of Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, C. J. Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There's so many of them that I could talk all night about bass players I like.
How did Pearl Jam manage to keep the grunge even though it's no longer in fashion?
I think we've all always felt slightly separated from the word grunge.
When it comes to grunge, I imagine the groups I referred to as Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana, and all the others that were created at the same time. And if music is so valid today, it's something great, because it's music worth listening to, and groups like Mudhoney are playing better music today than ever.
At the beginning, your music had a slightly bleak character and is now more positive.
What is behind this change?
This is interesting because I feel that in the new album there are a few tracks that are lighter coming along, but there are also songs such as The End or Juste Breathe, which are considered very bleak, although they may sound positive.
Both of them, when Ed played them for me, I cried, and they're songs deeply dark.
I think when you grow up and have some trauma in your life, you lose someone from a family or a friend, these things start affecting your art and music, and these two songs represent this to me.
I also think you can be a happy person and still make gloomy music.
