On the basis of the official file 197/2011, the legal pardon is granted to Jonah Larrazábal. In a trial against him, no complaint will be possible. Nor can it be claimed for damages or punishment.
After a trial with a legal agent around 15:50, the court ordered the immediate release of Larrazábal Bretón.
The court secretary, Jorge Yanéz, came to a prison in San Nicolás de los Garza to inform Jonah that he was granted official pardon and his case was postponed to archive.
He also announced to him that the judge issued an immediate order for his release.
Secretary Dionisio Pérez Jacome presented details of the air crash in which the Governor's secretary, Francisco Blake, and seven others died.
The Communications and Transport Secretariat (SCT) informed that the results of the accident investigation, in which the Secretary of Government Francisco Blake Mora and seven others died, show that the helicopter landed directly on the terrain with full force without the pilot having a chance to attempt forced landing.
At a press conference, Dionisio Pérez Jacome, Secretary for Communications and Transport, stated that before the start of the aircraft the pilot stated that the climate conditions allowed the flight.
"Parts that appear suggest that the unit came into contact with the terrain several times, wings entangled in tree branches 25 meters from where the unit lost the hull".
He also informed that the unit was intended for 19 people, therefore meeting all requirements for the transport of personnel.
In addition, he stated that no components were found on the ground on the basis of an investigation carried out in the field of impact.
"The search found that parts of the aircraft were not located elsewhere, so the aircraft crashed into the mainland as whole.
"The helicopter was intended for 19 people, meeting all requirements for passenger transport.
The terrain shows a slope with a slope of seven to thirty degrees.
The secretary assured that at the moment the most important thing is to get results as quickly as possible. However, the investigation may take several months or up to one year.
Gilberto López Meyer, the managing director of airports and auxiliary services stated that at the moment of impact, the helicopter of the Presidential General Staff was moving at cruise speed and the accident occurred on soft ascending terrain.
"This information supports the hypothesis that at the time of the accident it was a routine overflight operation", he said.
At a press conference, SCT Representative Pérez Jácome listed six basic points of inquiry:
Visual flight:
In accordance with aviation standards, the flight was carried out according to visual flight rules, meaning that the crew must see the terrain during the flight.
Meteorological conditions:
The AICM reports indicate adequate launch conditions, according to which the aircraft progresses towards the border, between DF and the State of Mexico visible layers of frowns at low altitudes.
Selected routes:
It is likely that due to clouds the crew sought a lower area and greater visibility up to the Cuernavaca valley.
Impact location.
The crash coordinates and the last radar recording match, it is likely that there was no loss of control or disruption of the flight trajectory prior to the impact.
Dissipation of aircraft residues in restricted territory:
The information we currently have allows us to assume that the impact occurred on a straight trajectory and from the side.
A sketch of the dissipation of the remnants of the aircraft suggests that at the time of impact on the mainland the helicopter was whole.
There was no fire or explosion.
No evidence was recorded at the scene of the accident to indicate that there was an explosion or a fire.
The latest results of the investigation show that there may have been several contacts with the mainland.
During field work, the remains of the aircraft were found at a height of up to 9200 feet above sea level, the terrain is sloped, the slope level goes from seven to 30 degrees.
The photographs show footage of the likely disintegration along that route.
The information provides elements that seem to suggest that the helicopter could have made contact with the ground in several places.
After a careful search in the vicinity of the accident, in a territory that is more extensive than the designated area, the remains of the helicopter were not found, which reinforces the assumption that the impact occurred in a state when the helicopter was still whole.
The Mexican Institute of Health Insurance began research into a gene that causes obesity
The Institute of Health Insurance conducts research to discover the gene responsible for obesity of children and adolescents.
The Mexican Institute of Health Insurance (IMSS) has announced that it conducts research to detect a gene causing obesity in children and young people. A research called "Genetics of Obesity in Children and Youth" will allow you to gain results on overweight.
In a report by the head of the Research Medical Unit in Biochemistry from the Specialized Hospital of the 21st Century National Health Center, Miguel Cruz López, explained that a multidisciplinary team consisting of doctors, nurses, nutrition professionals and social workers was established.
This team is based on the support of specialists and pupils of postgraduate studies from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Center of Research and Advanced Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
The general public, with or without permission, can also participate in research. People can come to participating IMSS sports centres in Valle de México, where every sober will be tested by teenagers from 8 am.
He stressed that research began at the Cuauhtémoc Sports Centre (Mexican State) and since 8 October this activity has also been carried out at the Nevahualcóyolt Sports Centre (East of the Mexican State).
Once data from 500 to 600 children are obtained, the study will continue at the Independencia Sports Centre (south of the Federal District) and finally at the Morelos Sports Centre (north of the Federal Centre).
He explained that the aim of this research is to identify the components and importance of genetics in terms of the development of obesity, and to trace to Mexican children and young people risk factors and thus prevent the emergence of chronic degenerative diseases.
On the occasion of the International Diabetes Day, which is celebrated on November 14, he recalled that the aim was to collect data from 3,000 children and young people between six and 14 years of age, with the consent and supervision of parents, for the application of specific nutrition questionnaires.
The questionnaire will also ask about physical activity and family history of hereditary diseases in order to avoid risk factors that could cause diseases such as diabetes or renal insufficiency.
It specified that anthropometric measurements (weight, height, waist circumference), blood pressure, glucose, triglycerides, cholesterol, insulin are carried out every Saturday for all participants (trying to identify genes involved in childhood obesity).
Cruz López said that this research reflects health care workers' concern over the alarming increase in child weight.
'Health polls conducted between 1999 and 2006 showed that only boys experienced a 77% increase in obesity and 47% increase in girls in just six years. There was also a dramatic increase in overweight', said an IMSS expert.
He stated that one reason for finding indicators is the assumption that the population of the country differs from other populations by its genetic history.
He informed that the average Mexican had 65% Indian-American genetic features, 30% European and 5% African. This is reflected in genes that are responsible for developing diabetes and overweight.
He explained that generally the genetics of obesity are commonly explained as an inability to burn the excess energy that we consume (calories) and which is stored in the form of fats.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit of the participants is that they receive an overall assessment of the condition of the children, thus establishing whether they show any known overweight or obesity.
He stated that even the presence of wrinkles of dark color (acantosis) on the neck and forearms indicates the probability that the individual will suffer metabolic problems and pre-scarcase conditions.
So far, the information is confidential, doctors give it to their parents in writing and explain to them all the measurements and lifestyle changes they have to make to avoid disease.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity, and other chronic diseases: a sedentary way of life meaning a lack of daily physical activity, a day-long sitting in front of television, and the use of means of transport instead of walking for short distances.
Overweight also causes large caloric intakes, i.e. greater consumption of sweetened beverages, carbohydrates (tamales, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with high fat and protein content and genetic burden that is the subject of this research.
There will be no potholes in Asfalt from UNAM
Rafael Herrera, a scientist from the UNAM Chemical Faculty, creates modified asphalts with polymers and creates a mixture with better functionality, independently of climatic conditions and temperature
If the paving was properly cared for, it would not be necessary to repair nearly 200,000 potholes after each rainy season in the Valle de México Metropolitan Region, Rafael Herrera Najer, a scientist from the Chemical Faculty (FQ) of UNAM, who also added that if the construction and maintenance of asphalt paving were adequate, there would be a significant reduction of potholes, or even could be completely removed.
In his lecture, the technological cause of the potholes he made during the International Year of Chemistry announced that the laboratory under his direction develops modified asphalts with polymers, thus creating a mixture with similar characteristics as asphalt, but also greater mechanical resistance, both at low and high temperatures.
Herrera Najera believes that this kind of modified tarmac could be used in places with extremely warm climates, such as in some cities in the north of the country, thus improving functionality and reducing the formation of potholes.
He explained that asphalt, the hardest part of oil, is the formation of hydrocarbons molecules, molecules with large molecular weights called asphalt, and others with low molecular weights called mortars. Together, they give asphalt a typical viscoelastic character.
Viskoelastic character of asphalt consists in that at high temperatures, around 180 degrees, behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees has high viscosity and at 50 degrees is almost in a solid state, while at low temperatures the asphalt tends to break, added.
This means that the resistance of asphalt in the streets is not uniform, but changes during the day according to weather conditions and temperature, alerted the expert on chemical engineering.
A science scientist from the Faculty of Chemical Sciences observed that most streets in Ciudad de México are covered with flexible tiles made up of six layers of materials, the last three of which are mixed with asphalt.
Among the top layers is an asphalt liner, consisting of small stones soaked in asphalt and then compressed.
He emphasized that every stone that forms a insert is covered with tarmac.
When passing cars or creating pressure, it is possible that the forces in the tile will break down well.
If it were modified asphalt, they would decompose even better, he thinks a chemical engineer.
He added that the last layer called the mantle, formed by fine stones, is placed on the tarmac insert, i.e. sand also soaked in tarmac.
As this layer will come into contact with the rims of vehicles, it must have greater mechanical strength than the asphalt liner and must ensure friction of the road.
As part of the paving will be exposed to heavy loads, the cloak must have sufficient thickness and be careful of the material from which it is made.
Climate, especially humidity and temperature changes, are also a very important factor to bear in mind. In particular, water has a great influence on the functionality of the tarmac liner.
Once the terrain is damp, the water spreads in and it is hard to get out, it causes softening of all layers of paving and thus the formation of potholes.
