Nord Stream, a new Russian gas entry port to Europe
The Nord Stream long-distance pipeline connecting Eastern Europe directly to Russia and led by the bottom of the Baltic Sea began to work.
They must supply gas equivalent to 30 million households.
Gazprom, a Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate this event properly.
Over 500 guests, among them 4 heads of state and government, participated in the Nord Stream inauguration last Tuesday, a new pipeline that connects Russia and Germany directly under the sea.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitriy Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch colleague Mark Rutte turned together by controlling the valve controlling the entry of Russian gas into the West European network.
With this new pipeline, 27.5 billion additional cubic metres of Russian gas will start flowing into Western Europe every year with the first 1 224 km pipeline connecting the region of Saint Petersburg with the Land of Mecklemburg-Pomorany.
The second pipeline to be completed at the end of 2012 will allow the supply of a total of 55 billion cubic metres of gas, which is a quantity equal to the whole of French consumption.
And it is already mentioned the possibility of building a third pipeline on the same route.
For Gazprom early completion of this huge structure has the character of victory.
Poland and the Baltic countries strongly protested the project.
In fact, Nord Stream will allow gas to be supplied directly to Germany without being run on the ground by a third State (Poland or Ukraine).
At the same time, these two countries are losing somewhat of power: the possibility of pushing Russia through threats to close its access to Western European markets is becoming more difficult for them.
Warsaw expressed it most strongly when she did not hesitate to compare Nord Stream to the "new German-Soviet Pact", with an appeal to the Hitler-Stalin alliance in the 1939 occupation of Poland.
It means saying that it is a subject of political sensitivities.
Western Europe has gained greater confidence in its purchases by supporting this Russian project.
But it is at the cost of weakening Europe's energy, because the project has created cracks between Europeans from east and west.
Russia has barely been able to assert its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western states with high gas consumption, whose deposits are nearing their end.
"This pipeline is part of our partnership with Russia, a new artery that links us organically", François Fillon confirmed during the opening ceremony of this pipeline and demonstrated the point at which large gas contracts of things are both political and economic.
All of this explains the broad smiles of Gazprom leaders present in large numbers in Lubmin, the gas supply point.
The construction of this pipeline is also an important technical act.
The underwater pipeline is made of steel fitted with a concrete casing to protect it from anchors of seagoing vessels.
It lies at the bottom of the sea at an average depth of 200 m.
During its construction, minefields originating in World War II had to be avoided.
"Because of security, almost a hundred had to be removed or destroyed", says Jens Müller, spokesperson for Nord Stream.
It was also necessary to increase measures to protect fauna and flora.
The pipeline itself is a long metal snake weighing as 242 Eiffelek, which is not interrupted by valves or maintenance stations anywhere on its entire length.
One control platform was to be built near Sweden, but the project leaders rejected it when the Swedes were little eager to see the Russian state company permanently settling off their coasts.
"In case of a malfunction, we stop gas passage in less than 1 minute", explains Jens Müller.
In the event of leaks, the gas contained in the pipeline escapes into the air.
But this case is considered unlikely by builders, for welds were designed to create leaks once every 100,000 years.
An offshore pipeline control is carried out by an underwater ship-drawn robot, while the inside of the pipeline is controlled by a device that circulates inside.
This cigar-shaped device with a diameter of 1 meter is introduced into the inside of the pipe and is pushed by gas.
In the target, it will provide accurate information on any deformations of metal parts throughout the three days of the journey at a speed of 3 m/s.
The long-distance pipeline was designed to operate for fifty years without the need for the slightest repair.
Circulation of gas is simply secured by pressure.
The value of this pressure is 200 bar at the start and 100 bar at the finish.
Five companies joined forces to implement this project.
Gazproma, which holds a 51% stake, remains the leader.
It was joined by the German companies E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as the Dutch company Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies formed a joint venture called Nord Stream entrusted with the construction and operation of the pipeline.
The company is based in the town of Zoug, Switzerland, where taxation is extremely advantageous.
Gazprom subsequently leased to the company for five years by a contract that can be renewed, all its gas transport capacities.
"Gazprom will have a profit from total capacity, whatever the amount of gas actually transported", explains Jens Müller.
Funding for pipeline construction was provided by 30% shareholder and 70% by bank loans.
The total labour costs should reach EUR 7.4 billion for both pipelines.
For the GDF Suez group, investment costs thus rose to 240 million.
But minority shareholders are sure that their costs will come back to them, because only Gazprom takes the risk.
The gas pipeline exits the Baltic Sea in Lubmin on a sandy coast with pine forests.
The valves of 4.5 meters high form the exit gate of the gas.
The sensors measure the pressure, temperature and other characteristics of the incoming gas before it is transported to German pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal has been receiving one million cubic metres of Russian gas every hour.
When full capacity is reached, it will be 3 million per hour and 6 million in 2012.
