Why is the unemployment rate of handicapped workers so high?
Around 19% of handicapped people are looking for work.
Today opens 15th week for employing handicapped people.
Despite the voluntarist public policy introduced in 2005, the percentage of unemployed handicapped people is even more than the average, i.e. 19% compared to 9% for the entire population.
Is that depressing?
"No, underscored by Éric Blanchet, CEO of Adapt Association, who organizes Week for employing disabled".
"The progress achieved in 15 years is remarkable".
"At the time, the percentage of unemployed were not twice, but three times higher."
"However, much remains to be done."
It should be said that for unemployed disabled people, numerous obstacles persist before their entry into work.
These are elderly: 37% have more than 50 years (17% average).
They have low qualifications: 80% have no graduation and out of 2.3 million college students there are only 10,000 handicapped.
Finally - long-term unemployment is very widespread: 53% for handicapped versus 38% on average.
In short, these are the criteria that make it particularly difficult to return to employment and which represent the "core of the problem", according to Christian Grapin, CEO of Tremplin, founded in 1992 to help businesses recruit disabled workers.
So much for objective brakes.
There are unspoken ways of thinking that certainly develop, but too slowly.
A study conducted in April by the IMS-Entreprendre pour la Cité Association found that interviewed managers have" a weak level of knowledge about handicapped persons" s" an exaggerated idea of people in a mobile chair and mental or mental deficiencies".
As a result, private businesses with more than 20 employees are still far from achieving the goal of employing 6% of the handicapped workers set out in the 1987 Act.
The most recent known figures dating back to 2008, indicate a state equal to 2.6%.
"We are now around 3%", says Pierre Blanc, CEO of Agefiph, charged with levying charges from businesses that fail to comply with this law.
The evidence is the number of" fined" enterprises, as well as the amounts paid, which fell between 2007 and 2011 from 59,000 more guilty enterprises to 46,000 (and from 606 to 480 million euro).
"The 2005 Act, which raised contributions, created strong pressure on businesses, explains Pierre Blanc".
"But this improvement also demonstrates true awareness, especially in large businesses."
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59% of businesses with 20 to 49 employees employ disabled workers compared to 82% of businesses with 100 to 199 employees.
